<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920313-0140</DOCNO><DOCID>920313-0140.</DOCID><HL>   Marketing andamp; Media:   BellSouth Corp.,   Dow Jones to Test   Voice Data Service</HL><DATE>03/13/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B8</SO><CO>   BLS DJ</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)UTILITIES (UTI)</MS><IN>MEDIA (MED)PUBLISHING (PUB)REGIONAL TELEPHONE SYSTEMS (RTL)TELEPHONE SYSTEMS (TLS)</IN><NS>JOINT VENTURES (JVN)NEW PRODUCTS andamp; SERVICES (PDT)</NS><RE>GEORGIA (GA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)NEW YORK (NY)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   ATLANTA -- BellSouth Corp. said it agreed with Dow Jones andamp;Co. to begin a joint market test of a voice-based informationservice for cellular telephone subscribers.   The new service, called Personal Info Clips, would providecustomers with customized, up-to-date news about business,the economy, stocks, bonds, commodities, sports, weather anda variety of other subjects. The service is scheduled tobegin tests Monday and will involve up to 5,000 customersthrough BellSouth's Los Angeles Cellular affiliate'svoice-mail service.</LP><TEXT>   Customers would access the information by calling up theirvoice-mail service.   If successful, BellSouth and Dow Jones plan to roll outsimilar versions of the service to additional BellSouthcellular markets and other voice-mail markets. Dow Jones'scharge for the service will be $2.25 a month, which will bebilled by BellSouth to customers' phone bills. In addition,cellular customers will pay normal air-time charges.   New York-based Dow Jones publishes The Wall StreetJournal, Barron's magazine and other periodicals, electronicbusiness information services and the Ottaway group ofcommunity newspapers.   BellSouth, a telecommunications holding company, provideslocal telephone service to nine Southeastern states, as wellas mobile telecommunications services, advertising andpublishing services, and communications systems.</TEXT></DOC>